{"cursor":"110516","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox MLB player |name=Barry Bonds |image=20060825 Barry Bonds follow\nthrough.jpg |caption=Bonds in August 2006 with the Giants |position=Left fielder\n|bats=Left |throws=Left |birth_date= |birth_place=Riverside, California\n|debutdate=May 30 |debutyear=1986 |debutteam=Pittsburgh Pirates\n|finaldate=September 26 |finalyear=2007 |finalteam=San Francisco Giants\n|stat1label=Batting average |stat1value=.298 |stat2label=Home runs\n|stat2value=762 |stat3label=Hits |stat3value=2,935 |stat4label=Runs batted in\n|stat4value=1,996 |stat5label=Stolen bases |stat5value=514\n|teams=\n* Pittsburgh Pirates (â)\n* San Francisco Giants (â) |highlights=\n* 14Ã All-Star (1990, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1995, 1996, 1997, 1998, 2000, 2001,\n  2002, 2003, 2004, 2007)\n* 8Ã Gold Glove Award winner (1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1996, 1997, 1998)\n* 12Ã Silver Slugger Award winner (1990, 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994, 1996, 1997,\n  2000, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004)\n* 7Ã NL MVP (1990, 1992, 1993, 2001, 2002, 2003, 2004)\n* 3x NL Hank Aaron Award winner (2001, 2002, 2004)\n* 1996 Home Run Derby winner\n* Holds numerous other records and achievements 'MLB Records'\n* 762 career home runs\n* 73 home runs in a season\n* 2,558 career walks\n* 688 career intentional walks }}\n\n\n }}\n\n\n\n'Barry Lamar Bonds' (born July 24, 1964) is a former American Major League\nBaseball outfielder. Bonds played from 1986 to 2007, for the Pittsburgh Pirates\nand San Francisco Giants. He is the son of former\nmajor league All-Star Bobby Bonds. He debuted in the Major\nLeagues with the Pittsburgh Pirates in 1986 and joined the San Francisco Giants\nin 1993, where he stayed through 2007.\n\nBonds is considered to be one of the greatest baseball players of all-\ntime. http://espn.go.com/mlb/feature/video/_/id/8652210/espn-\nhall-100-ranking-all-time-greatest-mlb-players http://www.baseball-\nalmanac.com/legendary/lisn100.shtml He has a record-setting seven Most\nValuable Player awards, including a record-setting four consecutive MVPs. He is\na 14-time All-Star and 8-time Gold Glove-winner. He holds numerous Major League\nBaseball records, including the all-time Major League Baseball home run record\nwith 762 and the single-season Major League record for home runs with 73 (set in\n), and is also the all-time career leader in both walks (2,558) and intentional\nwalks (688).\n\nBonds has led a controversial career, notably as a central figure in baseball's\nsteroids scandal. In 2007, he was indicted on charges of perjury and obstruction\nof justice for allegedly lying to the grand jury during the government's\ninvestigation of BALCO, by testifying that he never knowingly took any illegal\nsteroids. The trial began March 21, 2011; he was\nconvicted on April 13, 2011 on the obstruction of justice charge. On January 9, 2013\nBonds was denied entry into baseball's Hall of Fame in Cooperstown during his\nfirst year of eligibility on the ballot. {{cite news|url=http://www.suntimes.com/17478624-761/hall-of-fame-says-no-to-bonds-\nclemens-sosa.html|title=Hall of Fame says ânoâ to Bonds, Clemens, Sosa |accessdate=2013-01-09|date=2013-01-\n09|work=Chicago Sun-Times|author=Ginnetti, Toni}}\n","linknr":2769,"url":"Barry_Bonds","recorded":1362479202,"links":84,"instances":["baseball","pitcher","baseball","baseball","milwaukee","outfielder","baseball","trainer","major_league_baseball","baseball","baseball","baseball","baseball","baseball","baseball","baseball"],"pdf":["http://cdn.sfgate.com/chronicle/acrobat/2007/11/16/barrybondsindictment.pdf","http://web.archive.org/web/20071117084656/http://cdn.sfgate.com/chronicle/acrobat/2007/11/16/barrybondsindictment.pdf","http://cdn.sfgate.com/chronicle/acrobat/2007/11/16/barrybondsindictment.pdf"],"categories":["1964 births","Living people","African-American baseball players","American sportspeople in doping cases","Arizona State Sun Devils baseball players","Doping cases in ba